-- Gulf Coast Crudes Gain on Higher Refinery Demand, Lower Imports
-- B y   E l i o t   C a r o o m
-- 2013-04-22T18:23:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-22/gulf-coast-crudes-gain-on-higher-refinery-demand-lower-imports.html
Gulf of Mexico  crude grades
strengthened as refineries return from seasonal maintenance,
increasing demand.  Gulf Coast  refiners  used 8 million barrels a day of crude
in the week ended April 12, the most this year and 16 percent
more than 6.88 million in the seven days ended March 1, Energy
Information Administration data show. Imports to the Gulf, or
PADD 3 district, sank 9.5 percent in the same week.  Heavy Louisiana Sweet gained $1.50 to $13.25 a barrel over
U.S. benchmark West Texas Intermediate at 12:15 p.m. New York
time, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. HLS gained after
slipping April 18 to the narrowest premium since June. Light
Louisiana Sweet strengthened 80 cents to a premium of $12.80.  Poseidonâ€™s premium widened 85 cents to $7.10 a barrel.
Southern Green Canyon strengthened $1.15 to a $6 premium. Mars
Blend gained by 75 cents to $7.25 a barrel over the benchmark.  The premium for  Thunder Horse , which has a lower sulfur
content than Mars, Poseidon and Southern Green Canyon, was
unchanged at $9.25 a barrel.  Premiums for Eugene Island crude and Bonito Sour rose by 75
cents a barrel to $9.75 over WTI.  To contact the reporter on this story:
